00:00:26.230 --> 00:00:29.060
ANDREW W. LO: So on
behalf of the Sloan School

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:34.840
I want to welcome all of you
to 15.401 Finance Theory.

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:40.340
This course is meant for
first year MBA students.

00:00:40.340 --> 00:00:42.280
And so that's the
focus, and I'm going

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:46.050
to assume that that's the
background that all of you

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:46.990
will have.

00:00:46.990 --> 00:00:49.640
We may have a few other
students in the class,

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:53.020
but primarily it will
be first year MBAs who

00:00:53.020 --> 00:00:57.280
are thinking about
a career in finance,

00:00:57.280 --> 00:00:58.780
as well as those
of you who aren't

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:02.140
sure about a career in finance
but are curious about it.

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:05.170
Hopefully over the
next 13 weeks we'll

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:08.850
be able to satisfy
that curiosity.

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:12.090
I want to start by
talking a little bit

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:17.940
about what finance is, and
how I got interested in it,

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:20.520
because I think it's
often helpful in order

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.250
to motivate a subject
to get a sense of how

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:28.830
somebody else decided to
choose this as a profession.

00:01:28.830 --> 00:01:31.080
To do that I have to
go back a little bit,

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:33.910
and give you some
background about

00:01:33.910 --> 00:01:37.110
my own educational experiences.

00:01:37.110 --> 00:01:42.270
So let me start by
mentioning that I've

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:45.330
been at MIT for
the past 20 years,

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:48.540
and been in the finance
group all that time.

00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:51.730
Before that I taught at the
Wharton School for four years.

00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:53.940
And before that, I got
my PhD in economics

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:58.230
from Harvard University,
and then graduated in 1980

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:02.100
from Yale also
majoring in economics.

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:06.360
And during that time I've
learned an enormous amount

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:09.389
both about finance
and the real world,

00:02:09.389 --> 00:02:11.970
but one of the things
that I keep coming back to

00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:15.390
is the fact that
the finance field

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:20.460
is almost unique in how it
applies to practical management

00:02:20.460 --> 00:02:21.880
problems.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:25.260
And what I want to try to
do over the next 13 weeks

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:29.010
is to convince you of
the fact that finance

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:31.140
is in fact, the most
important subject

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:33.420
that you'll ever encounter.

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:37.470
That in fact, finance is
at the core of everything

00:02:37.470 --> 00:02:41.370
that you will ever do in
business and in management.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:44.250
Now that's a tall
order I recognize,

00:02:44.250 --> 00:02:45.780
and I suspect that
some of you are

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:49.050
quite skeptical about the
role that finance might play

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:50.590
in your own career objectives.

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:53.914
And I know many of you have very
different career objectives.

00:02:53.914 --> 00:02:55.830
And I'm not even trying
to convince all of you

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:58.260
to go into a career
in finance, but I

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:01.800
am trying to convince all of
you that finance is really

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:05.250
the lifeblood and
the basic lingua

00:03:05.250 --> 00:03:07.890
franca of all of business.

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:09.870
And that's one of the
reasons why finance

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:11.940
is such an important subject.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:14.800
Now before I begin, let
me ask you a question.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:20.350
How many people have had no
finance background whatsoever?

00:03:20.350 --> 00:03:22.150
Oh, that's great.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:25.554
I look forward to a challenge.

00:03:25.554 --> 00:03:26.970
But the other
reason it's great is

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:30.390
I have to tell you that it's
a real privilege for me to be

00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:34.080
here in front of you to
tell you about finance

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:35.190
for the very first time.

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:38.190
And it reminds me a
little bit of my younger

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:41.259
son who is an
extraordinarily fussy eater,

00:03:41.259 --> 00:03:42.300
he's eight years old now.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.210
But ever since he was born
he had some allergies,

00:03:45.210 --> 00:03:47.410
and he just refused to
eat most of everything.

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:51.210
In fact, my wife often says that
my younger son is a vegetarian

00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:53.550
except he doesn't
eat vegetables.

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:55.110
So he's an incredibly
fussy eater,

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:57.540
and somehow when
he was one year old

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:00.870
he saw my older son
eating an ice cream cone,

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:03.307
and figured that that's
something he ought to try.

00:04:03.307 --> 00:04:04.890
How he figured that
out, I don't know.

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:08.520
But he tasted it for
the very first time,

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.840
and you could see his face
change in about four seconds

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:17.490
from disgust to curiosity
to absolute, you know,

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:20.760
enthrallment with the taste
and feel of ice cream.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.334
He just loved it thereafter.

00:04:22.334 --> 00:04:24.000
That's one of his
major food groups now.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.560
It's ice cream.

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:29.040
And so I feel privileged to be
able to share that experience

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:31.999
here in the sense that once
you get a taste of finance,

00:04:31.999 --> 00:04:33.540
I think you're going
to be incredibly

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:35.460
excited and enthralled
by the subject.

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:37.140
Because it's one of
the few subjects,

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:39.900
in fact, that's the only
subject that I've encountered

00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:43.860
that is both rigorous,
it's extraordinarily

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:47.850
challenging from a research
and intellectual perspective,

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:51.460
and at the end of the day
it's extremely practical.

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:53.670
In fact, I would say
it's indispensable

00:04:53.670 --> 00:04:55.131
for financial management.

00:04:55.131 --> 00:04:57.630
So I'm going to try to convince
you of that over the next 13

00:04:57.630 --> 00:05:01.770
weeks, and I'm going to do
that by going over material

00:05:01.770 --> 00:05:04.515
that you will find
indispensable.

00:05:04.515 --> 00:05:06.390
As many of you know, at
the end of the course

00:05:06.390 --> 00:05:09.300
we have a ritual where we
hand out teaching ratings.

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:12.400
And among the finance faculty,
among all the faculty,

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.210
we're very concerned
about good teaching.

00:05:15.210 --> 00:05:17.670
So these teaching
ratings actually matter.

00:05:17.670 --> 00:05:21.390
And I've always thought that
having a teaching rating

00:05:21.390 --> 00:05:23.550
survey at the end
of the semester,

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:25.320
is somewhat misguided.

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:28.020
What I'd like to do,
and what I've proposed

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:30.360
hasn't been adopted
yet, I propose

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:32.610
to have teaching
ratings submitted five

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:35.100
years after a course is done.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:39.270
Now this may be a problem
for some people who aren't

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:40.920
up to speed in the classroom.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:43.920
But the reason I say this
is, because it will only

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:47.790
be after you get into your
jobs, into your careers,

00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:51.240
before you realize
how useful finance is.

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:54.510
And five years from now,
I suspect all of you

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:55.950
will come back
and say, gee, this

00:05:55.950 --> 00:05:58.325
is one of the most important
courses you have ever taken.

00:05:58.325 --> 00:06:01.290
Not because of me, but because
of the substance of what

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:03.240
we're going to cover
over the next 13 weeks.

00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:05.460
It's because of you
and all of the work

00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:08.050
that you will put
into this course.

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:10.470
This will be the most
challenging course

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:11.910
you will ever love.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:14.400
So I-- stealing
from the military--

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:16.740
I think that you'll
really appreciate

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:20.070
how the discipline
of financial logic

00:06:20.070 --> 00:06:22.980
will help you to think smarter
about all of your management

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:26.312
decisions no matter what you
decide to do with your careers.

00:06:26.312 --> 00:06:27.520
Now that's a very tall order.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:29.080
I've built up expectations.

00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:31.570
So I'm going to have to
deliver over the next 13 weeks,

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:34.070
and we'll see whether
or not we can do that.

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:37.150
But let me start now
by talking about what

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:39.120
we're going to cover today.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:41.940
I want to start with a
little bit of motivation,

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:44.430
and then talk about
the dramatis personae.

00:06:44.430 --> 00:06:46.890
These are the cast of
characters that we're

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:50.670
going to be focusing on
over the next 13 weeks.

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:53.400
And then I'm going to lay out
the fundamental challenges

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:54.640
of financial analysis.

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:58.210
It turns out there are only two.

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:01.000
There are only two challenges
in financial analysis,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.430
and once you figure both
of those out, you're done.

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:05.440
So if by chance you
can figure that out

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:07.023
before the end of
the class, you don't

00:07:07.023 --> 00:07:10.160
need to come back for
the rest of the lectures.

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:13.010
Then I'm going to
turn to providing you

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:15.650
with a framework for thinking
about these financial

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:16.970
challenges.

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:19.910
To me it's very important to
have a framework to start with,

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:21.770
because I like to
organize my thoughts

00:07:21.770 --> 00:07:23.999
into things that I know and
things that I don't know.

00:07:23.999 --> 00:07:26.540
And of the things that I know,
how did it relate to the stuff

00:07:26.540 --> 00:07:28.790
that I already knew,
or thought I knew.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:31.700
So I want to give you a sense
of that kind of framework

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:34.340
to think about financial
analysis upfront.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:38.230
You probably won't fully
appreciate it at this point,

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:42.126
but sometime over the next
13 weeks you will get it.

00:07:42.126 --> 00:07:43.500
And so I want to
give that to you

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:46.410
so that you can start thinking
about it subconsciously,

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:48.810
unconsciously, and
then eventually you

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:52.640
will understand how all
the pieces fit together.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:55.640
I then want to talk
about the importance

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:58.250
of two aspects of
financial analysis

00:07:58.250 --> 00:08:01.400
that make finance different
from every other discipline you

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:04.940
will ever encounter here
at MIT and elsewhere.

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:08.700
And that is time and risk.

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:10.500
Without those two
factors it turns out

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:13.990
that finance is actually done.

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:16.830
In other words, there's no
real research challenges,

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:21.810
no open questions left once
you eliminate time and risk.

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:24.300
Put in another way,
the only reason

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:27.180
that there exists a finance
department, and finance

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:30.630
faculty, and finance journals,
and a finance industry,

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:34.710
the only reason is
because of time and risk.

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:36.450
So I'm going to
come back to that.

00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:40.710
Then I'm going to conclude
by giving you the six

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.480
basic principles of finance.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:44.760
These are principles
that you will encounter

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:47.730
in all of your finance courses
for the rest of your stay

00:08:47.730 --> 00:08:49.480
at MIT and elsewhere.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:51.510
These are the ideas,
the fundamental ideas,

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:53.010
that have shaped
financial markets

00:08:53.010 --> 00:08:56.430
and that are at the root cause
of all of the financial market

00:08:56.430 --> 00:08:59.370
innovations, as well as all
of the financial market crises

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:01.740
that we've seen including
what's been going on

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.290
over the last several months in
the subprime mortgage market.

00:09:04.290 --> 00:09:06.623
In fact, we're going to talk
about the subprime mortgage

00:09:06.623 --> 00:09:09.360
problems after we cover
fixed income securities.

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:11.550
Right now I suspect
most of you know

00:09:11.550 --> 00:09:14.280
that there's something going
on, know that it's bad stuff,

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:16.260
but you don't know
why, how, where, when,

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:18.160
and what to do about it.

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:21.960
Well, in about five
lectures, you will.

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:25.110
It's not complicated, but
it's different from anything

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:26.580
that you've ever encountered.

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:28.920
And in fact, financial
analysis, I suspect,

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:32.130
is different from anything most
of you have ever encountered.

00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:34.260
I'm hoping that by
the end of the course,

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:38.370
it will change the way you
think about everything.

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:41.160
And again, I recognize
that that's a tall order,

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:42.570
but you tell me
13 weeks from now

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:45.240
whether or not I've delivered.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:47.400
And then I'll conclude by
talking about the course

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:49.110
overview, and then
finally I want

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:51.174
to say a few words
about how as a student

00:09:51.174 --> 00:09:52.840
you can get the most
out of this course.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:56.130
This is a part of the
lecture that I've always

00:09:56.130 --> 00:09:59.580
felt is critical at the
very start of a course

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:02.910
like this, because there
are a number of challenges

00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:04.950
that you will face
over the next 13

00:10:04.950 --> 00:10:07.239
weeks regarding this material.

00:10:07.239 --> 00:10:08.780
And I've always
thought that it would

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:12.676
be helpful for the instructor
to let me know where

00:10:12.676 --> 00:10:14.050
those challenges
might come from,

00:10:14.050 --> 00:10:16.650
and what I should do
in advance to prepare

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:17.580
for those challenges.

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:20.950
So I'm going to do that at the
end of this hour and a half.

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.740
For next time I'd like you
to read Brealey and Myers,

00:10:23.740 --> 00:10:25.660
chapters one and two.

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:30.320
We are going to be covering that
today as well as next Monday.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.710
So please keep up
with your readings.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:34.440
And at the end of
this lecture, I

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.780
will talk a bit about
the course requirements

00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:41.770
and other aspects of
the course mechanics.

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:44.990
Any questions?

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:47.300
All right, let me start
with some motivation

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:50.000
about why you might
want to study finance

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.610
and why finance is so important.

00:10:52.610 --> 00:10:56.570
And I've always found that with
motivation it's really best

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:59.210
to do it in a personal way.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:01.640
That is, to try to find
an individual or a group

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:05.810
of individuals that personify
a particular discipline

00:11:05.810 --> 00:11:06.657
or endeavor.

00:11:06.657 --> 00:11:08.240
And so there are
three people that I'd

00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:09.920
like to introduce you to.

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:13.610
I suspect you'll know at
least two out of the three,

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:17.020
but my guess is you
won't know all of them.

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:18.550
The first person--
oh, before I do

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:21.250
that, I want to introduce a
very simple definition of what

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:22.510
finance is.

00:11:22.510 --> 00:11:23.950
So this is the
very first equation

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:25.450
that you'll ever
see in this course,

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.370
and there'll be many
others of course.

00:11:27.370 --> 00:11:31.870
But the first expression
of exactly what is finance

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:37.750
is this, finance is simply
equal to mathematics plus money.

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:40.480
Now that suggests that
mathematics as a discipline

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:42.190
is equal to finance
without the money,

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:46.090
but really that's not my point.

00:11:46.090 --> 00:11:49.630
Although it's true by the
way, that's not my point.

00:11:49.630 --> 00:11:52.150
My point is that
finance is the study,

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:56.770
the systematic and disciplined
study of financial transactions

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:58.610
of money.

00:11:58.610 --> 00:12:01.356
Now when you see this you
might think, well, gee,

00:12:01.356 --> 00:12:03.230
I don't really have a
strong math background.

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:05.750
Maybe I'm in the wrong
place or the wrong class.

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:10.670
And I want to explain to
you that that's completely

00:12:10.670 --> 00:12:14.090
inaccurate, and inappropriate.

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:16.610
When I say mathematics,
I'm actually

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:20.390
talking about a very wide
range of mathematics.

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:23.240
Everything from
the extraordinarily

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:28.310
complex and profound to
the extremely pedestrian

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:29.720
and obvious.

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:34.340
So literally the range
from differential geometry

00:12:34.340 --> 00:12:35.870
and partial
differential equations

00:12:35.870 --> 00:12:40.430
on one end of the spectrum
to arithmetic and high school

00:12:40.430 --> 00:12:43.410
algebra at the other
end of the spectrum.

00:12:43.410 --> 00:12:46.340
Now since this is an
introductory finance class,

00:12:46.340 --> 00:12:48.570
I assume that you know nothing.

00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:51.120
What I mean by that
is, I assume that there

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:54.330
are no prerequisites that you
have other than what it took

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:56.370
for you to get
into here, which is

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:58.090
pretty substantial by the way.

00:12:58.090 --> 00:13:01.770
Congratulations to all
of you for getting in.

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:04.590
But we're not
requiring that you have

00:13:04.590 --> 00:13:09.540
any background in quantitative
analysis, computers,

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:11.220
upper level mathematics.

00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:15.250
So when I say finance is equal
to mathematics plus money,

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:17.320
there's a variety of
kinds of mathematics

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:18.910
that can be appropriate
for creating

00:13:18.910 --> 00:13:23.540
an extraordinarily profitable
career in this industry.

00:13:23.540 --> 00:13:27.100
And now here are
the three examples.

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:30.478
Anybody know who
James Simons is?

00:13:30.478 --> 00:13:32.434
Who is he?

00:13:32.434 --> 00:13:34.390
AUDIENCE: Well, I know
about Renaissance.

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:36.640
ANDREW W. LO: You know about
Renaissance Technologies.

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:39.010
Do you know what James
Simons did before he started

00:13:39.010 --> 00:13:41.369
Renaissance Technologies?

00:13:41.369 --> 00:13:41.868
Yeah.

00:13:41.868 --> 00:13:43.270
AUDIENCE: He's a math professor.

00:13:43.270 --> 00:13:46.360
ANDREW W. LO: He's a math
professor, that's right.

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.620
James Simons is
a math professor.

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:51.100
Well, was a math professor.

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:54.520
In fact, he was quite a
well-known math professor.

00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:56.890
When I first heard
of him, it wasn't

00:13:56.890 --> 00:13:58.510
because of Renaissance
Technologies,

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:00.850
which is a hedge
fund that he started

00:14:00.850 --> 00:14:03.720
about 15 or 20 years ago.

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:08.370
James Simons was a differential
geometer who for many years

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:10.740
was the chairman of
the math department

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:14.240
at Stony Brook in New York.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:20.000
And he authored with S.S. Chern
a particular field of study

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.020
in differential geometry called
Chern-Simons theory, which

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:26.240
has subsequently proved
to be extraordinarily

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:30.050
useful in an area of physics
known as string theory.

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:32.450
Extraordinarily abstract.

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:38.520
And Simon started a hedge
fund about 20 years ago.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:43.460
And this is probably the single
most successful hedge fund

00:14:43.460 --> 00:14:47.300
in the history of the industry
in terms of its performance

00:14:47.300 --> 00:14:48.770
record.

00:14:48.770 --> 00:14:52.610
Over the course
of 15 or 20 years,

00:14:52.610 --> 00:14:55.340
he's put together a track
record that has literally

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:58.310
beaten every other hedge
fund manager's track

00:14:58.310 --> 00:14:59.660
record by a lot.

00:14:59.660 --> 00:15:01.120
So it's not just a little bit.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:02.560
He's just sort of way out there.

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:06.530
He's the Michael Phelps
of quantitative investment

00:15:06.530 --> 00:15:08.060
strategies.

00:15:08.060 --> 00:15:10.910
By the way, just to give you
a sense of how successful

00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:13.210
he has been.

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:16.750
In 2006, two years
ago, it was reported

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.330
by Institutional
Investor's Alpha Magazine--

00:15:19.330 --> 00:15:21.830
this is a trade publication for
the hedge fund industry-- it

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:26.680
was reported that James Simons
was the single most highly

00:15:26.680 --> 00:15:29.200
paid hedge fund
manager that year

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:35.055
with a take-home
pay of $1.7 billion.

00:15:35.055 --> 00:15:38.700
Now, that's not
wealth, that's income.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:39.595
That was on his W-2.

00:15:42.630 --> 00:15:45.300
That was one year's
compensation.

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:47.120
And he did it--

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:50.570
he did this by building
a quantitative investment

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:54.680
management company with 75
PhDs in mathematics, physics,

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:57.110
computer science, and so on.

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:00.620
And nobody, nobody knows what
he does or how he does it.

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:03.590
It's extraordinarily secret.

00:16:03.590 --> 00:16:07.500
But there's no doubt that
he's incredibly successful.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:09.740
So that's one end
of the spectrum.

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:12.680
That kind of mathematics
can make money,

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:16.630
and can be extraordinarily
relevant financial analysis.

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:22.200
Now at the other end of the
spectrum, we have this guy.

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:25.240
You may have heard of
him, Warren Buffett.

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:28.630
He is currently the
richest man on earth.

00:16:28.630 --> 00:16:33.040
In 2008 Forbes ranked him
number one in terms of wealth.

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:38.794
At the time, February of 2008,
he was worth $62 billion.

00:16:38.794 --> 00:16:40.210
In fact, in a
private conversation

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:43.990
I was told that when Simons
found out he said, really?

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:44.920
$62 billion?

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:45.990
How did he get that?

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:47.350
It's amazing.

00:16:47.350 --> 00:16:50.320
That's an extraordinary amount
of wealth for an individual

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:51.190
to put together.

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:54.610
And what's extraordinary
about it, is how he did it.

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:57.850
As many of you know Warren
Buffett is an investor based

00:16:57.850 --> 00:17:00.130
in Omaha, Nebraska.

00:17:00.130 --> 00:17:06.099
His office is probably smaller
than many of the conference

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:07.869
rooms here at Sloan.

00:17:07.869 --> 00:17:10.660
The number of people he has
working for him, I suspect,

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.160
is fewer than many
of you who have

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:14.880
done your startups or plan to.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.310
He's got an extraordinarily
small staff.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:19.200
Mainly it's Charlie
Munger and him,

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:22.170
and a couple of
secretaries, and maybe

00:17:22.170 --> 00:17:27.140
a few accountants here and
there, and lawyers of course.

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:33.800
But what he does is to read
company prospectuses, income

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:35.930
statements, balance sheets.

00:17:35.930 --> 00:17:39.920
And with literally
high school arithmetic

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:43.890
he's built this incredible
investment empire

00:17:43.890 --> 00:17:46.200
by looking at valuation.

00:17:46.200 --> 00:17:47.560
Simple accounting.

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:50.220
Now I say simple accounting,
but there's nothing simple

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:52.420
about what he does.

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:55.860
And so clearly he
has certain skills

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:58.380
that also involve
mathematics, but not

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:02.230
the kind of mathematics
that James Simons uses.

00:18:02.230 --> 00:18:04.330
And finally, the
third individual

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:08.830
that I'd like to introduce you
to is this fellow, Jack Welch.

00:18:08.830 --> 00:18:11.650
Now again, many of you
know him or know of him.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:14.900
You know that he actually
teaches a course here at Sloan.

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:19.250
But you may not know
that his PhD was actually

00:18:19.250 --> 00:18:21.400
in engineering.

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:25.090
And he started out at
General Electric in 1960.

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:32.840
Became CEO in 1981, and
at that time the revenues

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:35.480
of General Electric was
about $26 billion a year.

00:18:35.480 --> 00:18:39.790
So it was already a big
and successful company.

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:43.000
And Jack Welch took
it over in 1981.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.470
At the time there were 400,000
employees for General Electric.

00:18:47.470 --> 00:18:50.950
Five years later, there
were 300,000 employees

00:18:50.950 --> 00:18:52.180
at General Electric.

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:53.666
He eliminated 100,000 jobs.

00:18:53.666 --> 00:18:56.290
That's one of the reasons why he
developed the nickname Neutron

00:18:56.290 --> 00:18:59.260
Jack, because like
a neutron bomb,

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:03.290
he eliminated a huge
segment of the population.

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:08.020
But five years later
with 300,000 employees,

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:10.720
he increased the market
value of General Electric

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:12.370
by several fold.

00:19:12.370 --> 00:19:17.410
And at the end of his tenure
in 2001, 20 years later,

00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:21.330
General Electric's revenues
was not $26 billion,

00:19:21.330 --> 00:19:23.530
it was $130 billion.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:26.770
He increased it by a
factor of 4 and 1/2

00:19:26.770 --> 00:19:28.720
over the course of 20 years.

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:30.940
It's an extraordinary
accomplishment

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:32.960
for an individual.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:35.170
Now why do I put him up here?

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:37.270
It's because one of
the things that Welch

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:39.020
did at General Electric,
one of the things

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:42.080
that he was extraordinarily
good at, was making

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:44.830
good decisions about
investments, making

00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:49.180
good decisions about costs,
being able to understand

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:52.960
the language of finance
despite the fact

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:56.810
that he used none of his
PhD skills in his job.

00:19:56.810 --> 00:20:00.110
He was an engineer by
training, not a manager.

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:02.680
He didn't go to
management school,

00:20:02.680 --> 00:20:05.410
although he did a lot
of executive education

00:20:05.410 --> 00:20:09.120
after his PhD.

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:11.640
The reason that I give you
these three cast of characters

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:16.110
is because they are so
different in what they do.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.450
They have such
different backgrounds.

00:20:18.450 --> 00:20:21.270
They're all
extraordinarily successful,

00:20:21.270 --> 00:20:23.690
but there's one thing in common.

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:28.410
The thing in common is that
they all understand innately,

00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:32.250
deeply, fundamentally,
the language of finance.

00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:34.980
And what we're going to
cover over the next 13 weeks,

00:20:34.980 --> 00:20:36.150
are the very basics.

00:20:36.150 --> 00:20:37.680
Things that they
take for granted.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:43.030
Things that they use on a
daily basis to do their jobs.

00:20:43.030 --> 00:20:45.540
So it's not to say that if
you do well in this course

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:48.240
you'll end up being
one of these guys,

00:20:48.240 --> 00:20:51.720
but it's certainly a
prerequisite I would say.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:54.450
There's nobody that's been
successful in business,

00:20:54.450 --> 00:20:58.290
truly successful, without having
an understanding, at least

00:20:58.290 --> 00:21:00.780
an innate or instinctive
understanding,

00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:03.780
of the concepts that we're
going to cover over the next 13

00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:04.950
weeks.

00:21:04.950 --> 00:21:06.150
So to me, that's exciting.

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:10.200
Now again, I'm not trying
to motivate you by greed.

00:21:10.200 --> 00:21:12.450
I'd rather motivate you by
the intellectual challenge

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:15.090
of finance, and there will
be some extraordinarily

00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:16.800
challenging ideas.

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:21.510
Ideas that are not natural
for any of you at this point,

00:21:21.510 --> 00:21:24.780
but which I hope
will be very natural

00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:27.960
at the end of this 13 weeks.

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:30.960
So let me start with
the cast of characters

00:21:30.960 --> 00:21:35.270
that we're going to be studying
over the next 13 weeks.

00:21:35.270 --> 00:21:38.950
There are going to be four
components of the economy

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:40.200
that we're going to focus on.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:41.950
Now this is a flow
diagram of the economy.

00:21:41.950 --> 00:21:44.560
Since we're at MIT we
have to have flow diagrams

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:46.030
at some point, right?

00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:49.900
So here's my version
of a flow diagram.

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:51.850
This is a flow model
of the economy,

00:21:51.850 --> 00:21:54.220
and there are four
components that

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:55.990
comprise the financial system.

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:59.560
Households, financial
intermediaries,

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:04.060
non-financial corporations,
and then capital markets.

00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:06.150
Now obviously the
economy is comprised

00:22:06.150 --> 00:22:09.270
of additional components like
labor markets and product

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:10.595
markets.

00:22:10.595 --> 00:22:11.970
We're not going
to focus on that.

00:22:11.970 --> 00:22:14.178
Although there are certain
financial aspects of those

00:22:14.178 --> 00:22:15.370
markets.

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:17.790
Given that we only
have 13 weeks,

00:22:17.790 --> 00:22:21.180
our attention will be spent
on those four components,

00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:24.090
and I'm going to cover each
of those four components,

00:22:24.090 --> 00:22:27.671
both in parallel and to a
certain degree sequentially,

00:22:27.671 --> 00:22:28.170
all right?

00:22:28.170 --> 00:22:30.246
So I want you to be
familiar with these four,

00:22:30.246 --> 00:22:31.620
because we're
going to be talking

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:35.490
about them interchangeably
at various points in time.

00:22:35.490 --> 00:22:39.000
Financial analysis applies
to all of these components

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:40.780
in exactly the same way.

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:43.320
But once you apply them
to the specific context,

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:46.350
the terminology may change,
the particular applications

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:47.430
may look different.

00:22:47.430 --> 00:22:49.920
What I'm going to try to
teach you in this 13 weeks

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:52.170
is the underpinning
theories that

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:55.710
unify all of the various
different kinds of ideas.

00:22:55.710 --> 00:22:57.690
So these are the four
components that we're

00:22:57.690 --> 00:23:01.510
going to be looking
at from now and then.

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:03.510
Now let me talk about the
fundamental challenges

00:23:03.510 --> 00:23:04.009
of finance.

00:23:04.009 --> 00:23:06.970
I told you that there
are only two, right?

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:08.590
And here they are.

00:23:08.590 --> 00:23:11.374
There are two aspects
of financial analysis

00:23:11.374 --> 00:23:12.790
that we're going
to be focused on.

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:17.500
The first is the
valuation of assets.

00:23:20.140 --> 00:23:26.170
And the second is very simply
the management of assets.

00:23:26.170 --> 00:23:27.040
That's it.

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:29.090
That's all there is to it.

00:23:29.090 --> 00:23:33.017
Valuing and managing.

00:23:33.017 --> 00:23:34.850
And I can tell you
exactly what the managing

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:37.100
part is going to look like.

00:23:37.100 --> 00:23:40.910
Managing is going to involve
figuring out which of two

00:23:40.910 --> 00:23:44.172
possibilities is more valuable.

00:23:44.172 --> 00:23:45.130
And then you know what?

00:23:45.130 --> 00:23:47.350
You take the more
valuable option.

00:23:47.350 --> 00:23:48.430
That's it.

00:23:48.430 --> 00:23:50.820
That's all there is to it.

00:23:50.820 --> 00:23:55.670
Figuring out the value, that's
going to be challenging.

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:59.210
So we're going to take
that first challenge

00:23:59.210 --> 00:24:03.290
to start with, and try
to understand valuation.

00:24:03.290 --> 00:24:04.910
I'm going to argue
that all business

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:07.970
decisions, any kind
of business decision,

00:24:07.970 --> 00:24:10.010
involves those two challenges.

00:24:10.010 --> 00:24:14.750
Valuing something, and
then once you value it,

00:24:14.750 --> 00:24:20.180
make a decision on what you
want to do with that value.

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:21.740
This is why I've
argued that finance

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:24.281
is the most important subject,
because literally any business

00:24:24.281 --> 00:24:26.270
decision that you
will ever engage in,

00:24:26.270 --> 00:24:27.860
constitutes those
two components.

00:24:27.860 --> 00:24:31.710
Valuation and management.

00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:36.570
Now valuation is going to
be a challenge by itself,

00:24:36.570 --> 00:24:40.060
because it's not at all clear
what value we're talking about.

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:43.980
In other words, what is value?

00:24:43.980 --> 00:24:46.090
Is water valuable?

00:24:46.090 --> 00:24:47.920
Well, life can't be
sustained without it.

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:50.140
At least carbon
based forms of life.

00:24:50.140 --> 00:24:52.640
So water is pretty valuable.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.650
But water is not that expensive.

00:24:54.650 --> 00:24:58.140
At least before Poland
Springs came along.

00:24:58.140 --> 00:24:59.190
Now what about diamonds?

00:24:59.190 --> 00:25:03.000
As far as I know, humans do
not need diamonds to survive,

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.240
and yet diamonds are
extraordinarily expensive.

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:10.060
There are certain gems
that are invaluable.

00:25:10.060 --> 00:25:11.510
Now how can that be?

00:25:11.510 --> 00:25:14.300
Clearly we have to
think more carefully

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:17.720
about what we mean by value.

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:20.840
And of course, once
value is established then

00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:24.130
management is
relatively easy to do.

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:28.690
Objectives plus valuations
obviously leads to decisions.

00:25:28.690 --> 00:25:31.310
So once you tell me what
you're trying to achieve,

00:25:31.310 --> 00:25:33.340
and then you value all
the various different

00:25:33.340 --> 00:25:36.640
possibilities, then I can tell
you what the right decision is.

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:40.330
Pick the decision that is the
most valuable for achieving

00:25:40.330 --> 00:25:43.470
the objectives that you want.

00:25:43.470 --> 00:25:45.680
Now that doesn't
really help a lot

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:49.010
if we can't apply this
to specific contexts,

00:25:49.010 --> 00:25:52.414
and come up with specific value.

00:25:52.414 --> 00:25:54.080
So I want to hammer
this home, and to do

00:25:54.080 --> 00:25:58.820
that I want to talk about how it
is that financial markets helps

00:25:58.820 --> 00:26:03.260
us establish value through
the price discovery mechanism.

00:26:03.260 --> 00:26:06.760
And to do that, I am going
to do a simple demonstration.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:09.410
Now when I was growing
up I went to one

00:26:09.410 --> 00:26:11.070
of these specialized
high schools

00:26:11.070 --> 00:26:12.070
that focused on science.

00:26:12.070 --> 00:26:14.570
So we were always getting
these various different kinds

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:19.287
of neat demonstrations of
the Tesla kind of coil.

00:26:19.287 --> 00:26:21.620
I've always been very jealous
