actually pretty fair.

00:37:27.617 --> 00:37:29.450
Now we're going to see
more examples of that

00:37:29.450 --> 00:37:31.430
over the next few weeks.

00:37:31.430 --> 00:37:35.180
Once we determine value, then
the question is management.

00:37:35.180 --> 00:37:36.890
How much should I save or spend?

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:39.200
That's a management
question that all of you

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:42.110
have to deal with at some
point or another in your lives.

00:37:42.110 --> 00:37:42.890
What should I buy?

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:44.180
What should I sell?

00:37:44.180 --> 00:37:46.220
When should I buy and
sell it, and how should I

00:37:46.220 --> 00:37:47.840
finance the transaction?

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:50.330
Those are the problems
of financial analysis

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:51.800
plain and simple.

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:55.190
These are problems that apply
to Jack Welch, to James Simons,

00:37:55.190 --> 00:37:56.990
to Warren Buffett, and to you.

00:37:56.990 --> 00:38:01.040
And it applies to you not just
from the corporate perspective,

00:38:01.040 --> 00:38:02.780
but from a personal
perspective as well.

00:38:02.780 --> 00:38:05.780
Every one of you have to
think about these issues

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:07.650
on a daily basis.

00:38:07.650 --> 00:38:11.510
And so finance
really is completely

00:38:11.510 --> 00:38:14.450
inclusive in the sense that it
applies to virtually everything

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:18.600
that you will ever
encounter in life.

00:38:18.600 --> 00:38:20.350
To do that I have to
go over the framework

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:25.610
of financial analysis, and the
starting point is accounting.

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:31.540
Accounting is the language,
the lexicon of finance

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:33.670
in that it's the
beginning of how

00:38:33.670 --> 00:38:35.770
to measure economic concepts.

00:38:35.770 --> 00:38:41.230
Like profit and loss,
revenues and costs, and so on.

00:38:41.230 --> 00:38:44.980
So while many of you may not
have accounting backgrounds,

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:48.380
you will learn a fair bit of
accounting in this course,

00:38:48.380 --> 00:38:50.890
just because you're going to
have to in order to understand

00:38:50.890 --> 00:38:53.410
the material in the lectures.

00:38:53.410 --> 00:38:56.110
So you'll need to get
familiar with the basic terms

00:38:56.110 --> 00:38:57.940
of accounting, and
in particular you're

00:38:57.940 --> 00:39:01.870
going to have to focus on two
concepts that are probably

00:39:01.870 --> 00:39:02.560
alien to you.

00:39:02.560 --> 00:39:05.850
The notion of a
stock and a flow.

00:39:05.850 --> 00:39:09.420
Now when I say stock, I don't
mean common stock or equities,

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:11.670
I have a different term in mind.

00:39:11.670 --> 00:39:16.290
By stock in this context,
I mean the stock of assets.

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:19.290
The level of assets.

00:39:19.290 --> 00:39:24.360
And by flow I mean the
rate of change of assets.

00:39:24.360 --> 00:39:26.380
You know when I
was in grad school,

00:39:26.380 --> 00:39:28.740
we started discussing this
concept on the first day

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:30.745
of macroeconomics, and
then one of the students

00:39:30.745 --> 00:39:32.870
in the back of the room
said, excuse me, Professor,

00:39:32.870 --> 00:39:36.600
but isn't that just the
distinction between a variable

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:38.750
and its first derivative?

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:42.400
And the professor was a little
bit taken aback and said,

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:43.400
well, yes, that's right.

00:39:43.400 --> 00:39:45.180
But let me give you another
way of thinking about it that

00:39:45.180 --> 00:39:46.400
is somewhat more intuitive.

00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:48.440
And that is, think
about a bathtub,

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:50.840
and think about the
faucet turned on

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:53.200
and the water flowing into it.

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:56.770
The stock is the
level of the water.

00:39:56.770 --> 00:40:01.910
The flow is how fast the
water is coming into the tub.

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:04.790
And so after that
explanation the student

00:40:04.790 --> 00:40:07.160
still seemed confused,
and so the professor said,

00:40:07.160 --> 00:40:09.364
you know what, some people
find bathtubs intuitive,

00:40:09.364 --> 00:40:11.030
other people find
derivatives intuitive.

00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:14.580
So to each his own.

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:16.680
These two concepts
are extraordinarily

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:18.720
critical to financial analysis.

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:22.800
And accounting counterparts are
nothing more than the balance

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:25.910
sheet and the income statement.

00:40:25.910 --> 00:40:29.750
The balance sheet measures the
stock of wealth of a company.

00:40:29.750 --> 00:40:34.280
What your assets are, and what
your claims on those assets

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:37.730
or liabilities are.

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:42.020
On the other hand, the flow
of wealth into a company

00:40:42.020 --> 00:40:45.980
or out of a company is measured
by the income statement.

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:47.810
This tells you how
much the company

00:40:47.810 --> 00:40:55.630
is making per unit
time versus its losses.

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:58.090
So the framework for
financial analysis

00:40:58.090 --> 00:41:00.400
that we're going to be
coming back to time and again

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:02.620
is this framework
of a corporation.

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:05.200
A corporation has a
certain set of assets.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:09.110
It's got claims on those assets,
which are called liabilities.

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:12.160
So this picture, this
snapshot, measures

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:13.960
the level of the bathtub.

00:41:13.960 --> 00:41:15.700
But that's not
enough to understand

00:41:15.700 --> 00:41:18.190
how a company is doing.

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:21.130
You also have to look at
the income statement, which

00:41:21.130 --> 00:41:25.480
tells you the sources of
funds, and the uses of funds

00:41:25.480 --> 00:41:26.950
over any time period.

00:41:26.950 --> 00:41:30.600
Typically on a quarterly basis.

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:33.680
So we're going to come back to
this concept as the framework

00:41:33.680 --> 00:41:35.510
for financial analysis.

00:41:35.510 --> 00:41:39.950
And by the way, this is
the sum total of the tools

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:44.800
that Warren Buffett uses for
analyzing his investments.

00:41:44.800 --> 00:41:46.010
That's it.

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:47.180
Believe it or not.

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:49.180
Nothing fancier.

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:51.640
So it's an incredibly
powerful set of ideas

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:57.370
if you know how to read it.

00:41:57.370 --> 00:41:59.380
That framework when
you think about it

00:41:59.380 --> 00:42:02.440
from a corporate financial
decision perspective,

00:42:02.440 --> 00:42:08.330
involves making decisions
at five points in time.

00:42:08.330 --> 00:42:11.540
Corporate financial
decisions involve

00:42:11.540 --> 00:42:16.470
thinking about how to deal with
cash raised from investors.

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:20.680
How to think about cash
invested in real assets,

00:42:20.680 --> 00:42:24.820
and how to deal with cash
generated by operations.

00:42:24.820 --> 00:42:28.450
How much cash to reinvest,
and how much cash you

00:42:28.450 --> 00:42:31.070
give back to your investors.

00:42:31.070 --> 00:42:33.610
So from this you
should get the idea

00:42:33.610 --> 00:42:36.550
that as a corporate
financial officer

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:39.610
you are focused on
cash, the flow of cash.

00:42:39.610 --> 00:42:45.220
In fact, cash you can think of
as the lifeblood of a company.

00:42:45.220 --> 00:42:47.890
If you follow the cash,
you will eventually

00:42:47.890 --> 00:42:51.400
hit upon every important aspect
of the modern corporation's

00:42:51.400 --> 00:42:52.690
operations.

00:42:52.690 --> 00:42:54.520
And as a financial
officer, you will

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:57.670
be responsible for
analyzing that flow.

00:42:57.670 --> 00:43:00.400
And as a decision maker, as
a leader of a corporation,

00:43:00.400 --> 00:43:03.130
you're going to have to make
decisions about that cash flow.

00:43:03.130 --> 00:43:06.160
Jack Welch uses the
information to be

00:43:06.160 --> 00:43:07.490
able to make those decisions.

00:43:07.490 --> 00:43:10.840
But he doesn't just get those
decisions prepackaged for him,

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:13.210
he has to understand
what those numbers mean.

00:43:13.210 --> 00:43:15.780
Just like Warren Buffett.

00:43:15.780 --> 00:43:20.470
Now the corporate financial
decisions involved,

00:43:20.470 --> 00:43:24.670
obviously, have a variety
of different components

00:43:24.670 --> 00:43:29.440
from a perspective
of career paths.

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:33.160
From the management perspective
real investment decisions

00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:35.290
involve two and three.

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:37.300
So if you're thinking
about investing

00:43:37.300 --> 00:43:39.730
in a new division or
a new plant or getting

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:41.710
involved in a new
product area, you've

00:43:41.710 --> 00:43:43.145
got to focus on two and three.

00:43:43.145 --> 00:43:45.520
On the other hand, if you're
the chief financial officer,

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:47.853
and you're thinking about how
should the company finance

00:43:47.853 --> 00:43:51.510
its operations, you're going
to be focused on one and four.

00:43:51.510 --> 00:43:53.230
If you're the
board of directors,

00:43:53.230 --> 00:43:56.620
and you're deciding how much
to pay out to the shareholders,

00:43:56.620 --> 00:43:58.470
you're going to be
thinking about five.

00:43:58.470 --> 00:43:59.890
And if you're
engaged in managing

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:01.390
the risks of the
corporation, you're

00:44:01.390 --> 00:44:03.790
going to be worried
about one and five.

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:07.330
And ultimately your
objective as a shareholder

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:10.760
and as a manager
of this corporation

00:44:10.760 --> 00:44:13.070
is to do well by the owners.

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:16.340
So your objective is to
maximize shareholder wealth,

00:44:16.340 --> 00:44:18.800
and the framework
that I've introduced

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:20.750
is going to allow
you to do that.

00:44:20.750 --> 00:44:23.480
Now again, this may seem
kind of theoretical to you,

00:44:23.480 --> 00:44:24.380
and I realize that.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:27.110
So I'm going to ask you to
make this more personal.

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:30.020
And to do that, I'm going
to ask you to turn this

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:32.690
into your own personal
household financial decision

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:34.260
making framework.

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:36.140
So I'd like you to
take all of these ideas

00:44:36.140 --> 00:44:38.960
and literally apply
them to yourself.

00:44:38.960 --> 00:44:42.680
Think about the
cash flows that are

00:44:42.680 --> 00:44:45.050
flowing through your own life.

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:48.320
There may not be that much right
now since you're at school,

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:51.500
but believe me, it will grow.

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:55.400
So the household,
this is you, sits in

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:57.750
between real
economic activities.

00:44:57.750 --> 00:45:00.830
In other words, your
job, and financial assets

00:45:00.830 --> 00:45:04.880
and liabilities, which are all
of the financial transactions

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:06.170
that you deal with.

00:45:06.170 --> 00:45:11.410
So this cash flow process that
I outlined for corporations, it

00:45:11.410 --> 00:45:13.360
works for you too.

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:17.350
So there's cash raised from
financial institutions, right?

00:45:17.350 --> 00:45:22.600
Like student loans or
borrowing or home equity loans.

00:45:22.600 --> 00:45:25.100
There's cash invested
in real assets.

00:45:25.100 --> 00:45:27.790
What's the biggest real
asset that you are all

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:29.117
investing in right now?

00:45:29.117 --> 00:45:30.450
AUDIENCE: Education [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:31.366
ANDREW W. LO: Exactly.

00:45:31.366 --> 00:45:32.640
Human capital, yourselves.

00:45:32.640 --> 00:45:35.250
Your own education.

00:45:35.250 --> 00:45:37.082
Cash generated by labor supply.

00:45:37.082 --> 00:45:38.540
Well, obviously,
when you get a job

00:45:38.540 --> 00:45:40.920
you're going to be
generating cash.

00:45:40.920 --> 00:45:43.740
Cash consumed and
reinvested in real assets.

00:45:43.740 --> 00:45:47.820
So consumed means beer
or pretzels or whatever,

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:49.500
and investing in
real assets means

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:53.580
you invested either in
yourself or you invest it

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:56.190
in a home or your children.

00:45:56.190 --> 00:45:57.584
Those are real assets.

00:45:57.584 --> 00:45:59.250
Sometimes they're
also real liabilities,

00:45:59.250 --> 00:46:00.960
but that's a separate issue.

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:05.327
And finally cash invested
in financial assets.

00:46:05.327 --> 00:46:07.410
Most of you may not have
a lot of financial assets

00:46:07.410 --> 00:46:09.870
at this point, but you
actually have some.

00:46:09.870 --> 00:46:13.542
I suspect 401(k) plans,
retirement, Social Security.

00:46:13.542 --> 00:46:16.000
Those are financial assets that
whether you know it or not,

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.490
you're invested in.

00:46:17.490 --> 00:46:20.730
And so when you think
about management,

00:46:20.730 --> 00:46:22.740
think about personal management.

00:46:22.740 --> 00:46:25.070
How are you managing yourself?

00:46:25.070 --> 00:46:26.820
You've got to think
about real investment.

00:46:26.820 --> 00:46:29.580
Consumption and financing,
savings and investment,

00:46:29.580 --> 00:46:32.790
risk management, and,
obviously, what is

00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:36.420
your overall objective in life?

00:46:36.420 --> 00:46:40.860
And what you ought to be doing
is with that objective in mind,

00:46:40.860 --> 00:46:43.710
managing your real
and financial assets

00:46:43.710 --> 00:46:49.680
to maximize the likelihood of
achieving those objectives.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:52.170
So what I'm asking you
to do is, I want you

00:46:52.170 --> 00:46:54.660
to take this course personally.

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:56.130
I want you to take the ideas.

00:46:56.130 --> 00:46:58.380
Every single idea
that I mention,

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:01.320
and whether I tell you to or
not for the next 13 weeks,

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:04.120
I want you to take that
idea and ask the question,

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:05.790
how does that make
my life better off?

00:47:05.790 --> 00:47:11.070
How can I use that in my own
personal management activities

00:47:11.070 --> 00:47:13.240
to improve the kind of
decisions that I'm making?

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:15.600
Because if you could
do that, if you

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:17.550
learn how to do
that instinctively,

00:47:17.550 --> 00:47:19.470
you will then take those
ideas and apply them

00:47:19.470 --> 00:47:21.661
to management contexts
in your career.

00:47:21.661 --> 00:47:23.160
And it will make
it much more likely

00:47:23.160 --> 00:47:25.170
that you'll get more
out of this course

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:27.820
than you otherwise might.

00:47:27.820 --> 00:47:29.920
Now there are two other
factors that I describe

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:33.520
that make financial
analysis challenging,

00:47:33.520 --> 00:47:40.970
and those two factors
are time and risk.

00:47:40.970 --> 00:47:43.910
I've argued before that
without these two elements

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:45.440
finance is complete.

00:47:45.440 --> 00:47:47.600
There is no more
research to be done.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:50.810
There's no more analysis
to be done, and all of you

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:55.520
probably will already be able
to intuit a lot of the decisions

00:47:55.520 --> 00:47:58.130
that you're going to
be forced to make.

00:47:58.130 --> 00:48:02.210
Because without time-- and
by time I mean decisions

00:48:02.210 --> 00:48:04.380
at different points in time--

00:48:04.380 --> 00:48:10.620
without time and without
risk financial decisions

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:14.250
actually reduce to basic
micro economic analysis.

00:48:14.250 --> 00:48:17.130
If you've taken an undergraduate
course in microeconomics

00:48:17.130 --> 00:48:19.230
supply equal
demand, well, you've

00:48:19.230 --> 00:48:22.110
learned all there is to learn
about finance without time

00:48:22.110 --> 00:48:24.210
and risk.

00:48:24.210 --> 00:48:27.510
The only reason that
finance is interesting,

00:48:27.510 --> 00:48:31.460
the only challenging
aspects of what we do

00:48:31.460 --> 00:48:35.230
are because of time and risk.

00:48:35.230 --> 00:48:39.220
The fact that cash flows
now are not the same as cash

00:48:39.220 --> 00:48:44.550
flows later, and that time
flows in only one direction.

00:48:44.550 --> 00:48:47.020
In about four
lectures, I'm going

00:48:47.020 --> 00:48:49.390
to give you an alternative
proof of the theory

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:51.720
of special relativity.

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:54.050
And this proof will
have to do with the fact

00:48:54.050 --> 00:48:57.020
that interest rates
are not negative.

00:48:57.020 --> 00:48:59.900
It turns out that there's a very
deep philosophical connection

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:03.022
between finance and physics
that we're going to get to.

00:49:03.022 --> 00:49:05.480
But this is something that you
don't need to be a physicist

00:49:05.480 --> 00:49:06.270
to understand.

00:49:06.270 --> 00:49:08.570
In fact, I'd argue
that Warren Buffett,

00:49:08.570 --> 00:49:13.270
although he may not be able to
articulate these principles,

00:49:13.270 --> 00:49:15.750
these are principles
that are somehow

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:18.090
inbred in his worldview.

00:49:18.090 --> 00:49:22.410
He knows that $1 today is
not the same as $1 next year.

00:49:22.410 --> 00:49:24.870
And he also knows that
$1 today without risk

00:49:24.870 --> 00:49:27.810
is not the same as $1 today
with a little bit of risk.

00:49:27.810 --> 00:49:31.440
Even a tiny little bit
of risk, he knows that.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:35.220
And at the end of this
course, you will too.

00:49:35.220 --> 00:49:38.640
So risk we have to talk about
in a much more serious way.

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:41.670
We're not going to get to
that for probably six weeks,

00:49:41.670 --> 00:49:46.170
because that's going to take
a whole different set of tools

00:49:46.170 --> 00:49:47.460
to understand.

00:49:47.460 --> 00:49:50.340
So what I'd like to do for
the first three or four weeks

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:55.080
is to focus on
time and just time,

00:49:55.080 --> 00:49:57.630
and then I'm going to bring
in risk once we develop

00:49:57.630 --> 00:50:02.000
a little bit more machinery to
understand how to capture risk.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.700
And when we put
these two together,

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:07.730
we're going to get
modern finance.

00:50:07.730 --> 00:50:13.220
So that will happen some time
in week six, seven, and eight.

00:50:13.220 --> 00:50:15.560
Now finally, I
want to talk about

00:50:15.560 --> 00:50:17.480
the fundamental
principles of finance,

00:50:17.480 --> 00:50:21.860
and then I'm going to talk
specifically about this course.

00:50:21.860 --> 00:50:27.440
There are six fundamental
ideas that finance has come up

00:50:27.440 --> 00:50:32.660
with that really will change the
way you think about the world,

00:50:32.660 --> 00:50:35.360
and you won't
appreciate it today.

00:50:35.360 --> 00:50:36.710
I know that.

00:50:36.710 --> 00:50:40.430
But I want to put it into
your subconscious today,

00:50:40.430 --> 00:50:44.000
because sometime over
the next 13 weeks,

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:49.220
at least I hope over the next 13
weeks, your face will light up

00:50:49.220 --> 00:50:50.972
and you're going
to get it one day.

00:50:50.972 --> 00:50:52.430
You're going to
get it in the sense

00:50:52.430 --> 00:50:54.890
that you will understand
at that point in time

00:50:54.890 --> 00:50:58.590
how these six
principles can be used

00:50:58.590 --> 00:51:02.160
to make any financial
decision that you need to make

00:51:02.160 --> 00:51:04.020
for the rest of your careers.

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:06.310
The first principle
is pretty obvious.

00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:09.030
There is no such
thing as a free lunch.

00:51:09.030 --> 00:51:11.790
Actually all of
these principles are

00:51:11.790 --> 00:51:14.950
approximations to a
much more complex truth.

00:51:14.950 --> 00:51:17.370
So if you really want
to be strict about it,

00:51:17.370 --> 00:51:20.430
it should read, there may
be free lunches on occasion,

00:51:20.430 --> 00:51:24.470
but there's no such thing
as a free lunch program.

00:51:24.470 --> 00:51:28.149
There isn't systematic
free lunches.

00:51:28.149 --> 00:51:30.440
You might be able to find
one or two every now and then

00:51:30.440 --> 00:51:33.280
if you're lucky and
if you work hard,

00:51:33.280 --> 00:51:38.530
but systematic transfers of
wealth for no reason at all

00:51:38.530 --> 00:51:41.270
are unlikely.

00:51:41.270 --> 00:51:42.980
Second principle.

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:44.840
Other things equal--
and this is a phrase

00:51:44.840 --> 00:51:47.417
that you'll hear economists
utter all the time.

00:51:47.417 --> 00:51:49.250
And of course, other
things are never equal,

00:51:49.250 --> 00:51:52.280
but let's pretend that they are.

00:51:52.280 --> 00:51:58.520
Other things equal, individuals
satisfy three characteristics.

00:51:58.520 --> 00:52:01.490
They prefer more money to less.

00:52:01.490 --> 00:52:05.250
That's often called
non-satiation.

00:52:05.250 --> 00:52:08.250
They prefer money
now to money later,

00:52:08.250 --> 00:52:12.840
and they prefer less
risk to more risk

00:52:12.840 --> 00:52:16.400
when risk is defined properly.

00:52:16.400 --> 00:52:18.130
Now I'd argue that
these principles

00:52:18.130 --> 00:52:21.070
are in fact fairly universal.

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:24.130
Not that you can't find
exceptions every now and then

00:52:24.130 --> 00:52:29.590
for every individual, but by
and large over periods of time

00:52:29.590 --> 00:52:33.820
and over a large population
this is generally true.

00:52:33.820 --> 00:52:35.590
And if you don't
believe me or if you

00:52:35.590 --> 00:52:39.170
know people that don't
satisfy these principles,

00:52:39.170 --> 00:52:41.420
please introduce them
to me after class.

00:52:41.420 --> 00:52:44.240
I'd like to get to know them,
and do some business with them.

00:52:48.270 --> 00:52:49.830
Principle three.

00:52:49.830 --> 00:52:54.400
All agents act to further
their own self-interest.

00:52:54.400 --> 00:52:57.610
Now again, this is not
to say that there aren't

00:52:57.610 --> 00:52:59.530
Mother Teresas out there.

00:52:59.530 --> 00:53:02.350
That there aren't people that
care about the general welfare

00:53:02.350 --> 00:53:04.120
of the public.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:07.990
But economists in their
own unique and annoying way

00:53:07.990 --> 00:53:12.250
have been able to redefine
preferences to even argue

00:53:12.250 --> 00:53:16.630
that Mother Teresa is incredibly
selfish, because her utility

00:53:16.630 --> 00:53:19.540
function is the
function-- the utility

00:53:19.540 --> 00:53:21.200
function of other people.

00:53:21.200 --> 00:53:23.290
And so by doing all
this good, Mother Teresa

00:53:23.290 --> 00:53:26.260
was only furthering
her own self-interests.

00:53:26.260 --> 00:53:28.650
Isn't she so selfish.

00:53:28.650 --> 00:53:33.610
Now, so in a way when the
economist defines preferences,

00:53:33.610 --> 00:53:36.820
they almost define
it as a tautology.

00:53:36.820 --> 00:53:40.660
But finance makes economics
practical in the sense

00:53:40.660 --> 00:53:44.830
that I'll describe in
a few weeks exactly

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:48.730
what kinds of preferences are
actually embodied in decision

00:53:48.730 --> 00:53:52.730
making, and why this principle
is more often than not,

00:53:52.730 --> 00:53:56.830
a pretty good approximation to
a much more complex reality.

00:53:56.830 --> 00:54:00.010
Now the last three
principles I'm not

00:54:00.010 --> 00:54:03.820
going to talk about in great
detail, because those really

00:54:03.820 --> 00:54:06.280
